##Face to face with state of emergency in the United States: a sudden change in social mood

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
By Jin Yan, CAIJING correspondent in Washington

Editor | Susie

Someone once told me that a good journalist should be aware of changes in social mood at all times.

On March 13, U.S. President Donald Trump announced the state of emergency, pledging the full commitment of the federal government and the cooperation of private companies to help more Americans affected by the outbreak, and open access to up to $50 billion. The announcement came as 48 of the 50 states and the District of Columbia reported nearly 1,800 cases and at least 41 deaths.

On March 13, U.S. President Donald Trump (center) formally announced the "state of emergency" at a news conference at the White House in Washington. He said the move was aimed at getting the U. S. federal government fully engaged in the fight against the new pneumonia. The initiative will free up $50 billion to help state and local governments deal with the epidemic. Photo / Xinhua

America's high profile entry into the state of emergency has actually been brewing for a few days. Declaring a national emergency means the federal government can devote more resources to fighting the epidemic and respond more flexibly and quickly. The president can also impose tougher measures in the name of a state of emergency. But Donald Trump hesitated. The source said he had his own concerns: First, that it would be a slap in the face, since he had been publicly downplaying the epidemic, equating it with seasonal flu, and second, that it could have a negative economic impact, wall Street in particular is concerned about the situation.

After much wrangling, Donald Trump invoked the Stafford act of 1988 to declare a state of emergency. The law would allow the Federal Emergency Management Agency to provide federal aid to state and local governments and coordinate a national response. National Emergencies are most often used for natural disaster events, but they are also used for disease outbreaks.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
As Donald Trump weighs and weighs, social sentiment in the US has changed dramatically in the space of a day or two.

Because of the time difference, the World Health Organization's announcement that the new pneumonia outbreak "has the characteristics of a global pandemic" reached Americans on March 12. For most Chinese, and for many in the health care system, the title of the belated pandemic means little now. But for most Americans, it represents an inflection point between the epidemic and public opinion.

My American friends, in a twist, began to talk about keeping a safe distance or isolating themselves, as if, one day, everyone was showing off eating, drinking, loving, showing off their pets, and the next, everyone was talking about the epidemic. And not just by saying it, but by sounding like a press secretary, anyone who calls on the American public to be vigilant.

Indeed, the American public's vigilance has risen sharply by several notches. "social distancing" has become a buzzword on twitter, with usage soaring.

Americans tend to be overconfident and overnervous, Jeffrey Young, a former global head of foreign exchange at Citigroup and co-founder and CEO of Deepmacro, explained to me.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(at MOM's Market, which specializes in organic food, the line of shoppers has shifted from one side of the mall to the other at closing time on the night of March 12, a sight that many workers are seeing for the first time. Photo: Jin Yan)

The outbreak is moving too fast

When pandemics like Ebola and bird flu strike, everyone is anxious. But no infectious disease has captured the headlines of the world for as long as the outbreak of coronary pneumonia. In the first month of the January outbreak, more than 41,000 english-language news articles mentioned the term "coronary pneumonia epidemic" in the headlines of nearly 19,000 articles, according to LexisNexis. By contrast, in August 2018, the first month of Ebola's outbreak, only about 1,800 english-language news articles mentioned the word Ebola, which appeared in the headlines of about 700 articles.

I don't remember anyone in the United States having any conversation with me about Ebola at the time, and even now Ebola is only used to compare and interpret a "coronary pneumonia epidemic. ". Ebola, whose death rate is tens of times greater than that of the disease, has received less than 3 percent of the attention.

It turned out that health care professionals in the United States were worried. On March 12, the nation's three largest health care organizations sent a letter to Vice President Michel Pense asking President Donald Trump to declare the state of emergency epidemic. The three organizations represent the hospital system, the nursing system, and the physician system in the United States. The move raised eyebrows because it was unprecedented.

More overt anxiety about the epidemic is on the market. All three indexes closed in a technical bear market on March 12. After just experienced the history of the second fuse, the U. S. stock market the same day again fuse.

For more than a month in the United States, the story was slow, and by March 12, it was too fast for many people to keep up. Hollywood star Tom Hanks and his wife were diagnosed with a new coronavirus in Australia and the NBA season was suspended. Neighbouring Canada's prime minister, Trudo, is facing a particularly thorny problem -- a virus that has been diagnosed in his wife. The president of the United States, of course, was not immune to gossip and spoofs, and the news and screenshots that Donald Trump had been duped into becoming a super spreader went viral.

In Washington, from the White House to the Supreme Court, the Capitol building and congressional offices have all declared closed to the public. Washington's proud Smithsonian Institution and National Zoo also announced that they would be closed to the public from Saturday.

After Congress canceled various hearings, I said in my circle of friends, if China cancels the second session, the United States will cancel the hearing. A lot of people joke that the United States dare to cancel the election? Democratic presidential hopefuls Biden and Sanders will actually hold a debate on Sunday, but because of the outbreak, the debate will have to be held without a live audience. I don't know if they're gonNA be less passionate in front of an empty auditorium. More shockingly, Louisiana has announced a delay in holding its presidential primary.

In New York, Broadway announced on the 12th that it would "immediately" suspend all performances. The word "immediately" generated a lot of discussion: People lamented that it had come so suddenly and so radically, and speculated that it would be followed by a series of blows that would make it so much more than a week ago that tourism brought in more than $26.7 million to the city.

By contrast, Universal Studios Hollywood and Disney were closed that day.

More broadly, people are going around looking for information about testing for the virus, and finding that American cities have the same problem: they don't have the ability to get anyone who wants to be tested tested. Robert Gordon, a sociologist, told me gloomily that American authorities have conflicting information about how to detect the virus, and the result is confusion and confusion.

One day half a month ago, Jeffrey Young in New York went to the supermarket just before midnight. It was a quiet time in America. He joked to me that he was hoarding food in response to the outbreak, and that his "big purchases" were what the Chinese call foreign wines. After the declaration of a national emergency in Donald Trump, he texted me that foreign wine served three purposes: to drink when the market crashed; to raise a glass when the market rose; and to talk as an alternative to sterilization when all the disinfectants on the market were sold out.

He wryly declared that it was wise to buy foreign wines, and today's rally was cause for celebration -- as Jeffery Young put it, after Donald Trump announced the state of emergency, the three major US stock indexes all rose by more than 9% , and the main indexes rose strongly in late trading, the Dow soared nearly 2,000 points. All three indexes posted their biggest one-day gains since the 2008 financial crisis. But foreign wine tastes bad when bought cheap, and Jeffery Young says the best option is to use it to sterilize.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(sterile water has been snapped up in the U. S. market for some time. Giant Superstore misannounced that disinfectant supplies would be available at 6 am on the 13th, sparking an early morning queue in Washington DC. Eventually people had to buy all kinds of materials and make their own disinfectant

The mask strikes back

In my entire American experience so far, masks have only been a topic of conversation once in my life.

It was a Sunday in February, and we had an early evening appointment at F's house. Before I left, I missed a lot of missed calls and text messages, and it took In & Out to realize that an American girl had taken a temporary leave of absence from the group: She had a bad cold and wasn't sure she could make it to dinner. F is the kind of humor and generous American gentleman, directly replied that even a cold must come!

F's words stirred the unease of a dozen Americans at the party. A medical man said sarcastically, come on, don't forget your mask. Others blame me for their insecurities. They share a common concern: it's flu season, and a coronavirus outbreak is spreading in other countries, and they don't want to be infected by an American girl. Either I find a mask for the American girl (in case she doesn't wear it) or I persuade the girl not to come, otherwise they won't be able to go to the dinner safely.

Once upon a time, one of our russian-american girls smelled too much and was too embarrassed to tell her to her face. But I mentioned to her the experience of disturbing people, tactfully and implicitly, both to take care of her dignity, but also to resolve the distress of others. I became famous in the first World War, and then when everyone complained, I was pushed to the front.

I looked it up, and I actually have a mask, which I used to protect myself from the smog in China a few years ago. But it's impossible to force someone to wear a mask. Finally, I spent an hour persuading American girls to rest at home, persuading f not to insist, and reassuring the others to attend the dinner on time.

The role of the mask as a life episode has been complicated by the surge in new cases in the United States, which has created a huge wave. Since the outbreak of the epidemic in Wuhan has been extremely tense, to Wuhan new cases for the first time fell to 5 still extremely tense, is the Chinese Americans.

I was drawn into a Chinese regional outbreak group, which discussed everything from new cases in the area, whether to work from home, whether to stock up on guns, and, of course, more questions from souls with or without masks. A Chinese American and I joked that we are all good knowledge, but there are war crazy complex.

After I wrote about the outbreak in my column in Washington, a lot of people asked me if I needed to send masks from home? My response was always: Don't bother, for fear of being hooded -- Asian "hooded and beaten" was in the news from time to time, and then there was the news of being hooded and beaten... There are few cases of a face mask being beaten, and it is simply a new outlet for racists, some of whom chalk it up to cultural differences between China and the West.

I don't remember any branch of Chinese culture with masks. As for why Western culture repels mask, I ask the Westerner everywhere, nobody admits this has anything to do with cultural heritage.

Cultural differences aside, it's more practical to look at the issue from a disease prevention perspective. It is widely believed in Asia that one of the most effective ways to stop the spread of pneumonia is to isolate the transmission route and wear a mask. But most Americans tell me that they are simply following the propaganda of US public health officials, that masks are useless, and that only symptomatic people, or those who are already ill, need to wear them.

The truth is more complicated than that. Huang Yanzhong, a senior fellow in global health at the council on Foreign Relations, told me his story: He had just gotten over a cold and was coughing a lot. He had been invited to a Congressional hearing the other day and had traveled all the way from New York to Washington, D.C. , wearing a face mask on the train, which he thought would be polite to fellow passengers and a "please stay away" signal. But soon there were people sitting next to him because they liked the window seat.

That was quickly reversed. An article circulating among my American friends on March 12th called for global health policymakers to rethink the use of face masks. The paper, published in The Lancet Medical Journal, suggests that some public health researchers believe the virus is "challenging conventional containment strategies" -- as if those infected may be asymptomatic in the early stages of infection, or just mild symptoms. Traditionally, people wear masks to prevent transmission from contact between sick and healthy people, but wearing masks with or without symptoms also protects people by controlling the source of the virus.

Looking carefully at the people on the street, the taxi drivers and the supermarket crowds, I found for the first time that more non-asians in the greater Washington area were wearing masks than Asians on that day.

Robert Hendler, a former Parkland associate dean and chief quality officer, is now a chief medical officer and clinical professor at the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center. He gave me a very professional answer.

He was blunt about the shortage of face masks in the United States, and to avoid mass hoarding, public health officials recommended that only the sick use masks to reduce the spread of the virus, as well as to save limited resources. If the outbreak becomes more widespread in the United States and the number of infections increases rapidly, then a more effective way to reduce human-to-human transmission is to wear a mask.

At the political level, in addition to the political implications of putting a mask on Donald Trump's face on magazine covers, the shortage of masks has also exposed the short sightedness of American politicians. The public health crisis has shown that over the past two decades, the federal budget has been unable to cope with a growing number of threats to spending, including terrorist attacks, natural disasters and deadly infections.

The Washington Post notes that the 2009 H1N1 outbreak prompted the largest deployment of the Strategic National Stockpile, which turned out to be the last large federal Stockpile of drugs and medical supplies. The U.S. public health system is running down its inventory to control its budget and expects the private sector to supply it quickly in the event of an outbreak; with a limited annual budget of $600 million, since then, the federal government has not significantly restocked its medical reserves, including the N-95 mask. The health system needs 3.5 billion masks a year, and the U.S. currently has only 1% of those.

Robert Hendler concludes that this is how risk versus benefit works: If everyone wore N-95 masks, the risk of transmission would quickly decline. Because the number of cases in the United States is relatively small, the need for masks to be widely used has not yet been met so that the benefits of wearing masks can not be realized, unlike in the case of China.

At noon on the 13th I took part in a think-tank conference call to discuss the epidemic. When it comes to masks, experts at the think tank say the N-95 masks are mostly made in China, leaving a big gap in the United States. I told Robert Gordon that we were too dependent on China.
